com.seagullsw.appinterface.client

Interface AppInterfaceConnection

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    BasicAppInterfaceConnection, CicsEngineAppInterfaceConnection, HTTPAppInterfaceConnection, SocketAppInterfaceConnection, SslAppInterfaceConnection, TextAppInterfaceConnection

    public interface AppInterfaceConnection

    The AppInterfaceConnection interface represents a single client connection to the Application Interface Server. Concrete instances of classes implementing this interface are obtained via static createXxxConnection() calls to the factory class AppInterfaceConnectionFactory, for example in order to supply such a connection to the AppInterfaceCommand.AppInterfaceCommand(AppInterfaceConnection) constructor for a Java command bean.

    An AppInterfaceConnection object can be used to execute a single application interface function request in its own session, simply by invoking the execute(Request) method with a Request object as an argument, or else the execute(String) method with an XML string encoding the request.

    Alternatively, to ensure that all execute() calls from the client run in the same session within the server, the connection can be opened (via the open() method) and reused to execute a series of requests, then finally closed (via close()).

    An AppInterfaceConnection object can also maintain arbitrary client context information by means of the methods getClientSessionContext() and setClientSessionContext(Object).

    See Also:
    BasicAppInterfaceConnection, AppInterfaceConnectionFactory, AppInterfaceCommand

      • execute

        com.seagullsw.appinterface.model.data.Response execute(com.seagullsw.appinterface.model.data.Request request)
                                                throws java.io.IOException

        Sends a Request object to the back-end for execution, and returns a Response object.

        If the connection has not explicitly been opened with open(), then it will automatically be opened, the request executed in a separate session, and finally the connection closed. Alternatively, the connection may first be opened explicitly, after which all subsequent invocations of execute() will be processed in the same session until the connection is explicitly closed with close(). In this regard, see also AppInterfaceCommand.execute().

        NOTE: This method is not currently intended for general use by clients.

        Parameters:
        request - The Request to execute.
        Returns:
        The execute Response
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • execute

        java.lang.String execute(java.lang.String requestText)
                  throws java.io.IOException

        This string-oriented variant of the execute(Request) method accepts requests and returns responses encoded in the XML runtime data syntax specified in the chapter "XML Interfaces of the Application Interface Server" of the "Application Interface Programming Reference Manual."

        If the connection has not explicitly been opened with open(), then it will automatically be opened, the request executed in a separate session, and finally the connection closed. Alternatively, the connection may first be opened explicitly, after which all subsequent invocations of execute() will be processed in the same session until the connection is explicitly closed with close(). In this regard, see also AppInterfaceCommand.execute().

        Throws:
        java.io.IOException
